<header>
<h1>Our Land</h1>
<p><img src="hughes-america.jpg" class="a" /></p>
<h2>by Langston Hughes</h2>
</header>
<main style="display:flex;justify-content:center">
<div>
<p class="intro">We should have a land of sun, <br /><br />
Of gorgeous sun, <br /><br />
And a land of fragrant water<br /><br />
Where the twilight is a soft bandanna handkerchief<br /><br />
Of rose and gold, <br /><br />
And not this land<br /><br />
Where life is cold.</p><br />
<p>We should have a land of trees,<br /><br />
Of tall thick trees,<br /><br />
Bowed down with chattering parrots<br /><br />
Brilliant as the day,<br /><br />
And not this land where birds are gray.</p><br />
<p>Ah, we should have a land of joy,<br /><br />
Of love and joy and wine and song, <br /><br />
And not this land where joy is wrong.</p>
</div>
</main>
<hr>
<footer>
<p>“Our Land” appeared in The New Negro: An Interpretation, edited by Alain Locke (Albert and Charles Boni, 1925).</p>

